<font color="#FF0000">CAN I BE A REMF?</font><br>
<tt>Wed Aug 13  2:43:09 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Chet and Art:<br><br>
Since I brought up the word or acronym REMF maybe I should define.  I don't know everybody's definition of REMF.  But mine doesn't include people like you.  As a helicopter pilot I spent a lot of time in the rear... took more showers than a whole battalion of grunts... ate a little Ice cream at the Officer's club in Tan Son Nhut.  I'm damned sure no REMF... or am I? <br>
A lot of Grunts are half REMF. After a tour in the boonies they were occassionally fortunate enough to move back.  Some unfortunate M-60 operators left the bush to become REMF door gunners on helicopters.  Oops! Bad move... alot of those REMF's died.<br>
A lot of guys, who did better in eight grade math than me, kept me from getting blown out of the sky... using radios and some quick stressful thinking (Thanks Art and Chet!)<br>
While we are at it I suppose we can call the Air Force and Navy Pilots real REMF's. Some of those worthless bastards sat out the whole war in some comfortable cage in North Viet Nam while us psuedo REMFs burned shit and filled sand bags.<br>
Let's not forget the medical REMFs.  Boy were they lucky!  They could look at guts an bones all day every day and rejoice because it wasn't there bones and guts.  Boy, did they have it easy!<br>
My idea of a REMF is not where you were or what you were doing... It is more of where you weren't and what you weren't doing.  There were REMFs (in country)in air conditioned trailers whose main objective was furthering their military careers without getting their clothes dirty.  You know who I am refering to... those guys who would pick up the radio and send living grunts to their death to get a body count for their gluttoneous REMF cohorts in the Pentagon.<br>
But, Chet and Art... if you guys really want to be REMFs... well then move over a notch and make room for me... I enjoy good company.<br><br>
Mustang Two Four
